he following:"},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`compatkey.dat`</ph> is a strong-name key file.","pos":[11183,11225],"source":"`compatkey.dat` is a strong-name key file."},{"content":"This command creates a strong-named assembly you can place in the global assembly cache.","pos":[11226,11314]},{"pos":[11322,11403],"content":"[!NOTE]\n Publisher policy affects all applications that use a shared component.","leadings":["","> "],"nodes":[{"content":"Publisher policy affects all applications that use a shared component.","pos":[9,79]}]},{"content":"The publisher policy configuration file overrides version information that comes from the application (that is, from the assembly manifest or from the application configuration file).","pos":[11410,11593]},{"content":"If there is no statement in the application configuration file to redirect the version specified in the assembly manifest, the publisher policy file overrides the version specified in the assembly manifest.","pos":[11594,11800]},{"content":"However, if there is a redirecting statement in the application configuration file, publisher policy overrides that version rather than the one specified in the manifest.","pos":[11801,11971]},{"content":"A publisher policy file is used when a shared component is updated and the new version of the shared component should be picked up by all applications using that component.","pos":[11978,12150]},{"content":"The settings in the publisher policy file override settings in the application configuration file, unless the application configuration file enforces safe mode.","pos":[12151,12311]},{"pos":[12322,12331],"content":"Safe Mode","linkify":"Safe Mode","nodes":[{"content":"Safe Mode","pos":[0,9]}]},{"content":"Publisher policy files are usually explicitly installed as part of a service pack or program update.","pos":[12335,12435]},{"content":"If there is any problem with the upgraded shared component, you can ignore the overrides in the publisher policy file using safe mode.","pos"